\c 1
\p 
\v 1 The words of Qoheleth, the son of David, king in Jerusalem:
\p 
\v 2 “Vapor of vapors!” says Qoheleth. “Vapor of vapors! Everything {is} vapor!”
\p 
\v 3 What profit {belongs} to humanity in exchange for all his toil that he will toil under the sun?
\p 
\v 4 A generation is going and a generation is coming, but the earth is standing in perpetuity.
\p 
\v 5 And the sun rises and the sun comes and, panting to its place, it is rising there.
\p 
\v 6 Going southward and turning northward, turning, turning, the wind is going and on its circuits the wind is returning.
\p 
\v 7 All the rivers are going to the sea, but the sea—it is not full. To a place that the rivers are going, there they are going again.
\p 
\v 8 All things {are} wearisome; a person is not able to speak. An eye is not satisfied of seeing, and an ear is not filled from hearing.
\p 
\v 9 Whatever that was, it will be, and whatever that has been done, it will be done. And there is not anything new under the sun.
\p 
\v 10 {Is} there a thing about which one says, “See this—it {is} new?” It already existed in ages that were from before our faces.
\p 
\v 11 There is not a remembrance of the former things, and even of the latter things which will be, there will not be remembrance of them with those who will be afterwards.
\p 
\v 12 I, Qoheleth, I was king over Israel in Jerusalem.
\p 
\v 13 And I gave my heart to seek out and to explore with wisdom concerning everything that is done under the sun. It {is} an unpleasant business God has given to the sons of humanity to be busy with it.
\p 
\v 14 I saw all the deeds that are done under the sun and—look—everything {is} vapor and striving {after} wind.
\p 
\v 15 What is bent is not able to be straightened, and what is missing is not able to be counted.
\p 
\v 16 I spoke, I with my heart, saying, “Look at me—I have become great, and I have added wisdom over all who were to my face over Jerusalem. And my heart saw much wisdom and knowledge.”
\p 
\v 17 And I gave my heart to know wisdom and knowledge, madness and folly. I knew that this also, it {is} striving {after} wind.
\p 
\v 18 For with an abundance of wisdom {is} much vexation and one who is adding knowledge is adding pain.
\c 2
\p 
\v 1 I said, I in my heart, “Come, let me test you in joy and examine good.” But look, it also {was} vapor.
\p 
\v 2 To laughter, I said, “{It is} madness,” and to joy, “What is this doing?”
\p 
\v 3 I explored in my heart {how} to drag my flesh with wine—but my heart was guiding {me} in wisdom—and {how} to grasp folly until I could see whether this {is} good for the sons of humanity that they might do under the heavens {during} the number of the days of their lives.
\p 
\v 4 I enlarged my deeds. I built for myself houses. I planted for myself vineyards.
\p 
\v 5 I made for myself gardens and royal parks and I planted in them a tree of each fruit.
\p 
\v 6 I made for myself pools of waters to cause to drink from them a forest of growing trees.
\p 
\v 7 I acquired {male} servants and female servants and sons of the house belonged to me. Also much property of cattle and sheep belonged to me, more than all who were to my face in Jerusalem.
\p 
\v 8 I also amassed for myself silver and gold and treasure of kings and the provinces. I appointed for myself {male} singers and female singers and the pleasures of the sons of humanity: breast and breasts.
\p 
\v 9 And I was great, and I added more than all who were to my face in Jerusalem. Also my wisdom stood by me.
\p 
\v 10 And all that my eyes asked, I did not refuse from them. I did not restrain my heart from any joy, because my heart {was} joyful from all my toil and this was my portion from all my toil.
\p 
\v 11 And I turned, I, to all my works that my hands had done and to {the} toil that I toiled to do and look, everything {was} vapor and striving {after} wind, and there was no profit under the sun.
\p 
\v 12 And I turned, I, to see wisdom and madness and folly, because what {is} the person {to do} who will come after the king? That which {is} already, they have done it.
\p 
\v 13 And I saw, I, that there is a profit for wisdom more than folly, as {there is} a profit of the light over the darkness.
\p 
\v 14 The wise, his eyes {are} in his head, but the fool in the darkness is walking, and I know, even I, that one happening will happen to both of them.
\p 
\v 15 And I said, I in my heart, “As {the} happening of the fool, also {to} me, it will happen to me. And why was I myself wise back then, abundantly?” And I said in my heart that also this {is} vapor.
\p 
\v 16 For there is no remembrance of the wise {person} with the fool in perpetuity, because already {in} the days {that} have come both {are} forgotten—and how will the wise die with the fool?
\p 
\v 17 And I hated life because of {the} misfortune around me—the work that was done under the sun—because everything {was} vapor and striving {after} wind.
\p 
\v 18 And I hated, I, all my toil that I had toiled under the sun that I will leave it to the person who will be after me.
\p 
\v 19 And who knows: will he be wise or a fool? And he will have authority over all my toil that I have toiled and {for} which I have acted wisely under the sun. Also this {is} vapor.
\p 
\v 20 And I turned, I, to cause my heart to despair concerning all the toil which I toiled under the sun.
\p 
\v 21 For there is a person whose toil {is} in wisdom and in knowledge and in skill, but to a person who has not toiled in it, he will give it {as} his portion. This also {is} vapor and a great misfortune.
\p 
\v 22 For what endures for the person in exchange for all his toil and in the striving of his heart {in} which he {is} a toiler under the sun?
\p 
\v 23 Because all his days {are} pains, and anger {is} his business, even in the night, his heart does not rest. Also this—it {is} vapor.
\p 
\v 24 There is no good for humanity {except} that he will eat and drink and cause his spirit to see good in his toil. Also this I saw, I, that it {is} from the hand of the God.
\p 
\v 25 For who will eat and who will enjoy apart from him?
\p 
\v 26 For to a person who is good to his face, he gives wisdom and knowledge and joy. But to the sinner he gives {the} business to gather and to collect to give to {the} one who is good to the face of God. This also {is} vapor and striving {after} wind.
\c 3
\p 
\v 1 For everything {there is} a season and a time for every matter under the heavens:
\p 
\v 2 a time to give birth and a time to die, a time to plant and a time to tear out what was planted,
\p 
\v 3 a time to kill and a time to heal, a time to break down and a time to build,
\p 
\v 4 a time to weep and a time to laugh, a time to mourn and a time to dance,
\p 
\v 5 a time to throw stones and a time to gather stones, a time to embrace and a time to refrain from embracing,
\p 
\v 6 a time to seek and a time to lose, a time to keep and a time to throw away,
\p 
