\p 
\v 19 Because the happening of the sons of humanity and the happening of the animal—{there is} one happening for them. As the death of this one, so the death of this one. And {there is} one spirit for them both, but an advantage of humanity over the animal, there is none, for everything {is} vapor.
\p 
\v 20 Both are going to one place. Both are from the dust, and both return to the dust.
\p 
\v 21 Who knows {that} the spirit of the sons of humanity, it {is} the one going up, upwards, and the spirit of the animal, it {is} the one going down, downwards to the earth?
\p 
\v 22 And I saw that there is nothing better than that humanity will rejoice in his works, for it {is} his portion. For who will bring him to look at what that will be after him?
\c 4
\p 
\v 1 And I turned, I, and I saw all the oppressions that were being done under the sun. And, look, the tears of the oppressed and there was no comforter for them. And from the hand of the ones oppressing them {was} strength and there was no comforter for them.
\p 
\v 2 So I praised, I, those who were dead, who have already died, more than the living, who they are still alive.
\p 
\v 3 But better than {the} two of them {is} the one who has not yet lived, who has not seen the evil-doing that is being done under the sun.
\p 
\v 4 And I saw, I, every toil and every success of the deed, that it {was} the envy of a person from his friend. This also {is} vapor and striving {after} wind.
\p 
\v 5 The fool is folding his hands and is eating his flesh.
\p 
\v 6 Better {is} a full palm of quiet than the full hollow of both hands with toil and striving {after} wind.
\p 
\v 7 And I turned, I, and I saw a vaporous thing under the sun:
\p 
\v 8 There is one {person} and there is not a second {person}—even a son or brother, there is not for him—and there is no end to all his toil. Also his eye is not satisfied {with} wealth. And why {am} I toiling and causing my soul to lack from good things? Also this {is} vapor and it {is} an unpleasant business.
\p 
\v 9 Better are the two {people} than the one {person}, that there is for them a good wage in exchange for their toil.
\p 
\v 10 For if they fall, the one {person} will lift up his companion, but woe to him, the one {person} that will fall, but there is no second {person} to lift him up.
\p 
\v 11 Also, if two {people} lie down, then there is warmth for them, but for {the} one {person}—how will there be warmth?
\p 
\v 12 And if he will overpower him, the one {person}, the two {people} will stand against him, and the three-fold rope will not be torn in two quickly.
\p 
\v 13 Better is a poor but wise child than an old but foolish king who does not yet know {how} to be warned.
\p 
\v 14 For from the house of those who are imprisoned he came forth to become king, yet even in his kingdom he was born poor.
\p 
\v 15 I saw all the living, those walking around under the sun, with {that} second child who will stand under him.
\p 
\v 16 There {was} no end to all the people, to all who were to their faces. Even the ones {who will be} afterward will not rejoice in him, because even this {is} vapor and striving {after} wind.
\c 5
\p 
\v 1 Keep your feet when you go to the house of God. And to draw near to listen {is better} than fools giving a sacrifice, for they are not knowing {that they} do evil.
\p 
\v 2 Do not be in haste concerning your mouth, and do not let your heart hurry to bring forth a word to the face of God. For God {is} in heaven, but you {are} on the earth; therefore, let your words be few.
\p 
\v 3 For the dream comes with much business and the voice of a fool {comes} with many words.
\p 
\v 4 When you vow a vow to God, do not delay to fulfill it, for there is no delight in the fools. What you vow, fulfill.
\p 
\v 5 {It is} better that you not vow than that you vow but do not fulfill.
\p 
\v 6 Do not give your mouth to cause your flesh to sin, and do not say to the face of the messenger that it {was} an unintentional sin. Why should God be angry concerning your voice and destroy the deed of your hands?
\p 
\v 7 For in many dreams and vaporous things and many words—just fear God.
\p 
\v 8 If {the} extortion of {the} poor and {the} robbery of justice and righteousness you see in the province, do not be amazed concerning the matter, for a high one over a high one is watching, and high ones {are watching} over them.
\p 
\v 9 And a profit of a land in everything, it {is} a king for a worked field.
\p 
\v 10 A person who loves silver will not be satisfied {with} silver and whoever loves increase {will} not {be satisfied with} income. Also this {is} vapor.
\p 
\v 11 When the good {thing} increases, the people eating it increase. And what advantage {belongs} to its master except the sight of his eyes?
\p 
\v 12 Sweet is the sleep of the worker, whether a little or whether much he will eat, but the satisfaction of a rich person—it is not permitting for him to sleep.
\p 
\v 13 There is a sickening misfortune I have seen under the sun: wealth kept by its master to his harm.
\p 
\v 14 And that wealth perished in an unfortunate business, and he had fathered a son, but there was not anything in his hand.
\p 
\v 15 As he went out from the womb of his mother, naked he will go again, as he came. And he will not take anything in exchange for his toil that he will bring in his hand.
\p 
\v 16 And also this is a sickening misfortune: just as he came, thus he will go, and what profit {belongs} to him who will toil for the wind?
\p 
\v 17 Also, all his days in darkness he will eat, and {in} great vexation and his sickness and anger.
\p 
\v 18 Look, what I myself have seen {is} good: that {it is} fitting to eat and to drink and to see good in all his toil that he will toil under the sun {during} the number of the days of his life that God has given to him, for it {is} his portion.
\p 
\v 19 Also, each person who God has given to him wealth and possessions and has empowered him to eat from it and to accept his portion and to rejoice in his toiling—this, it {is} a gift of God.
\p 
\v 20 For not much does he remember the days of his life, because God occupies {him} with the joys of his heart.
\c 6
\p 
\v 1 There is a misfortune that I have seen under the sun and it {is} great on humanity:
\p 
\v 2 a person who God gives to him wealth and possessions and honor, and he has no lack for his soul from all that he desires, but God does not enable him to eat from it; instead, a foreign person will eat it—this {is} vapor and it {is} a sickening misfortune.
