\v 3 If a person should father a hundred {children} and he should live many years and {however} many that the days of his years may be, but his soul is not satisfied from the good {thing} (and also a burial place is not for him), I said, “Better than him {is} the stillborn child.”
\p 
\v 4 For in vapor it came and in the darkness it will go and in the darkness its name will be covered.
\p 
\v 5 Even {the} sun it did not see, nor did it know. {More} rest {belongs} to this one than this one.
\p 
\v 6 And if he lived a thousand years twice over, but a good {thing} he did not see—are not both going to one place?
\p 
\v 7 All the toil of humanity {is} for his mouth, and yet the soul is not filled.
\p 
\v 8 For what advantage {exists} for the wise over the fool? What {advantage} {exists} for the poor person that knows {how} to walk before the living?
\p 
\v 9 Better {is} a sight of {the} eyes than the walking of {the} soul. Also this {is} vapor and striving {after} wind.
\p 
\v 10 Whoever that was, already his name has been called, and it is known that he {is} a human being. But he is not able to strive with who is more powerful than he.
\p 
\v 11 For there are many words {that} are increasingly vaporous—what {is the} advantage for humanity?
\p 
\v 12 For who is knowing what {is} good for humanity in life {during} the number of the days of his vaporous life? And he makes them like the shadow. For who will declare to humanity what will be after him under the sun?
\c 7
\p 
\v 1 Better is a {good} name than fine oil and the day of death {is better} than the day of his birth.
\p 
\v 2 Better to go to a house of mourning than to go to a house of a banquet, because it {is} the end of all humanity and the living will give {it} to his heart.
\p 
\v 3 Better grief than laughter, for with a bad face a heart is made good.
\p 
\v 4 {The} heart of wise people {is} in a house of mourning, but {the} heart of fools {is} in house of joy.
\p 
\v 5 Better to listen to a rebuke of a wise person than {to be} a person listening to a song of fools,
\p 
\v 6 for like the sound of the thorns under the cooking-pot, so {is} the laughter of the fool. And this also {is} vapor.
\p 
\v 7 For oppression drives a wise person insane, and a bribe destroys a heart.
\p 
\v 8 Better is an end of a thing than its beginning. Better is a long spirit than a high spirit.
\p 
\v 9 Do not hasten in your spirit to become angry, for anger rests in {the} lap of fools.
\p 
\v 10 Do not say, “What was {it} that the former days were better than these?” For you do not ask about this out of wisdom.
\p 
\v 11 Wisdom is good with an inheritance and an advantage to those who see the sun.
\p 
\v 12 For {as} in the shadow of wisdom, {so} in the shadow of silver. And {this is} an advantage of knowledge: wisdom preserves her owners.
\p 
\v 13 See the work of God, for who is able to straighten that which he has made it crooked?
\p 
\v 14 In the good day, be in good, but in a day of misfortune, see— indeed, God has done this as well as this, so that humanity cannot find anything after him.
\p 
\v 15 I have seen everything in the days of my vapor: There is a righteous person perishing in his righteousness, and there is a wicked person lengthening {his days} in his evil.
\p 
\v 16 Do not be very righteous and do not be exceedingly wise—why should you be shocked?
\p 
\v 17 Do not be very wicked and do not be a fool—why should you die when {it is} not your time?
